prediction.region: my studies, I have found the secrets of the stars. The books that I have written about them serve as examples to our greatest doctors. My judgment in this matter has been excellent. I have also discovered the secrets of trees, plants, and stones, along with their various uses. Yet, I consider all of this knowledge to be of little value. I wish that I were ignorant and knew nothing of these things. As I have discovered, this knowledge does not better a person in goodness, but rather makes him proud and think too highly of himself. What has all my knowledge of nature's secrets gained me? Only the loss of a better knowledge, the loss of divine studies that make the immortal part of man, his soul, blessed. They all implored me to spare the books because they contained things that future generations could greatly benefit from. However, I did not listen to them and threw all the books into the fire, burning the greatest learning in the world. Then I distributed all of my wealth, giving some to poor scholars and some to other poor people. I left nothing for myself. I had a cell built in the church wall and locked myself inside, where I remained until my death. I spent my time in prayer, meditation, and other divine exercises, seeking through all means to purify my soul.

What hath all my knowledge of natures secrets gained me ? Onely this, the losse of a better knowledge, the losse of divine studies, which makes the immortall part of man his soule blessed. I have found, that my knowledge has beene. a heavy burden, and has kept downe my good thoughts but I will remove the cause, which are these bookes which I doe purpose here before you all to burne. They all intreated him to spare the bookes, because in them there were those things that after-ages might receive great benefit by. He would not hearken unto them, but threw them all into the fire, and in that flame burnt the greatest learning in the world. Then did he dispose of all his goods some part he gave to poor schollers, and some he gave to other poore folkes nothing left he for him-selfe then caused he to be made in the church-wall a cell, where he locked himselfe in, and there remained till his death. His time hee spent in prayer, medita-tion, and such divine exercises, and did seeke by

prediction.region: my studies, I have found the secrets of the stars. The books that I have written about them serve as examples for our greatest doctors, so excellent is my judgment in this area. I have also discovered the secrets of trees, plants, and stones, with their several uses. Yet, I esteem all of this knowledge so lightly that I wish I were ignorant and knew nothing. The knowledge of these things serves only to make a person proud and think too well of themselves, but it does not improve a person's goodness. What has all my knowledge of nature's secrets gained me? Only the loss of a better knowledge, the loss of divine studies that make the immortal part of a person, their soul, blessed. I have found that my knowledge has been a heavy burden and has kept down my good thoughts. But, I will remove the cause - these books which I purpose to burn before you all. They all pleaded with me to spare the books, as they contained knowledge that future generations could benefit from. I would not listen to them, but threw all the books into the fire, burning the greatest learning in the world. Then I disposed of all my goods, giving some to poor scholars and others to other poor folks. I left nothing for myself except causing a cell to be built in the church wall, where I locked myself in until my death. I spent my time in prayer, meditation, and divine exercises, seeking to become closer to God.

ocr.region: 290 CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. XXXV Cette crise fut plus longue que ceile qui avait prcd, et il y eut un moment o le mdecin dsespra du succs. Ce n'tait plus l'action du poison qui tait  craindre, mais l'ef-fet de cette secousse morale sur une organisation dj pro-fondment atteinte. Ludovic s'accusait et se dsesprait, il rejetait sur lui la responsabilit de cette rechute, et parlait de suivre la jeune fille si elle n'en rchappait pas. Il demandait pardon au doc-teur de n'avoir pas mieux suivi ses conseils et offrait de quitter la chambre afin de ne pas compromettre de nouveau les effets de son traitement. Mais celui-ci avait rflchi, et cette fois son avis fut tout oppos. - Non, lui dit-il, restez. - Mais si je commets encore quelque imprudence ? - Restez, vous dis-je, le mal est fait. Vtre prsence a amen une crise, votre absence en amnerait une auire, plus fcheuse encore. Je ne connaissais pas cette enfant c'est une tte de fer. Il faut que vous soyez l, quand elle reprendra ses sens. Restez. - J'obis alors. - Et que le ciel vous inspire, Ludovic, quand le moment sera venu. Cette jeune fille a au coeur une plaie dont je ne puis la gurir et que la Facult en corps ne gurirait pas c'est le dgot de la vie. Tchez d'en venir  bout et j'incli-nerai ma science devant la vtre. L'aimez-vous ? - Si je l'aime 1 Vous me demandez si je l'aime! Ne le voyez-vous pas ? - Eh bien 1 alors, il y a quelque chance pour que vous russissiez. Mais, ou je me trompe fort, ou ce sera une cure difficile. Cet entretien avait lieu  voix si basse, que rien n'en pou-vait parvenir aux oreilles de Marguerite, et, pourtant, il se fit chez elle un mouvement singulier. Sa main, raidie et con-racte, se replia d'elle-mme et vint se poser sur sa poi-

Ludovic s'accusait et se dsesprait, il rejetait sur lui la responsabilit de cette rechute, et parlait de suivre la jeune fille si elle n'en rchappait pas. Il demandait pardon au doc-teur de n'avoir pas mieux suivi ses conseils et offrait de quitter la chambre afin de ne pas compromettre de nouveau les effets de son traitement. Mais celui-ci avait rflchi, et cette fois son avis fut tout oppos. -Non, lui dit-il, restez. -Mais si je commets encore quelque imprudence ? -Restez, vous dis-je, le mal est fait. Votre prsence a amen une crise, votre absence en amnerait une autre, plus fcheuse encore. Je ne connaissais pas cette enfant c'est une tte de fer. Il faut que vous soyez l, quand elle reprendra ses sens. Restez. -J'obis alors. -Et que le ciel vous inspire, Ludovic, quand le moment sera venu. Cette jeune fille a au coeur une plaie dont je ne puis la gurir et que la Facult en corps ne gurirait pas c'est le dgot de la vie. Tchez d'en venir  bout et j'incli-nerai ma science devant la vtre. L'aimez-vous ? -Si je l'aime ! Vous me demandez si je l'aime ! Ne le voyez-vous pas ? -Eh bien ! alors, il y a quelque chance pour que vous russissiez. Mais, ou je me trompe fort, ou ce sera une cure difficile. Cet entretien avait lieu  voix si basse, que rien n'en pou-vait parvenir aux oreilles de Marguerite, et, pourtant, il se fit chez elle un mouvement singulier. Sa main, raidie et con-racte, se replia d'elle-mme et vint se poser sur sa poi-

prediction.region: This crisis lasted longer than the previous one, and there was a moment when the doctor despaired of success. It was no longer the action of the poison that was to be feared, but the effect of this moral shock on an organization already deeply affected. Ludovic accused himself and despaired, he blamed himself for this relapse, and spoke of following the young girl if she did not recover. He apologized to the doctor for not having followed his advice better and offered to leave the room so as not to compromise the effects of his treatment again. But this time, the doctor had thought about it, and his opinion was entirely different. - No, he said, stay. - But if I make another mistake? - Stay, I tell you, the harm is done. Your presence has brought on a crisis, your absence would bring on another, even worse. I didn't know this child, she's a head of iron. You must be there when she comes to her senses. Stay. - Then I will obey. - And may heaven inspire you, Ludovic, when the time comes. This young girl has a wound in her heart that I cannot heal, and the Faculty as a whole would not be able to heal it either; it is the disgust for life. Try to overcome it, and I will bow my science before yours. Do you love her? - If I love her? You ask me if I love her! Can't you see it? - Well then, there is some chance of success. But, unless I am very much mistaken, it will be a difficult cure. This conversation was held in such a low voice that nothing could be heard by Marguerite, and yet there was an unusual movement in her hand. It became stiff and contracted, and then moved on its own to rest on her chest.

ocr.sentence: matter the king was very glad hereof, and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg-ment that I shall appoint they all answered, that they were.
ocr.region: OF FRYER BACON. 221 the matter the kingwas very glad hereof,and caused the combatants to be brought before him, to whom he said gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversie shall be ended that is now amongst you Are you contented to stand to his iudg ment that I shaU appoint they all answered, that they were. Then were they bid to returne three days after. In that time Fryer Bacon had caused the body of their deceased father to be taken out of the ground, and brought to the court the body hee did cause to be bound to a stake, naked to the middle upwards and Hkewise prepared three bowes and shafts for the three brethren all these kept hee secretly. The third day being come, came these three brethren, to whom Fryer Bacon in the presence of the king gave the three bowes and shafts, saying, be not offended at what I have done, there is no other way but this to judge your cause See here is the body of your dead father, shoot at him, for he that cometh nearest to his heart, shad have aU the lands and goods. The two eldest prepared themselves, and shot at him, and stucke their arrowes in his breast. In the matter, the king was very glad hereof and caused the combatants to be brought before him. To them, he said, "Gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversy shall be ended that is now amongst you. Are you contented to stand to his judgment that I shall appoint?" They all answered that they were. Then they were asked to return three days later. 

During this time, Friar Bacon had exhumed the body of their deceased father and brought it to the court. He then bound the body to a stake, leaving it naked from the middle upwards. He likewise prepared three bows and arrows for the three brothers. All of these he kept in secret. 

On the third day, the three brothers returned. Friar Bacon then gave them the three bows and arrows in the presence of the king, saying, "Be not offended at what I have done. There is no other way to judge your cause but this. See here is the body of your dead father. Shoot at him for he that comes nearest to his heart shall have all the lands and goods." 

The two eldest brothers shot their arrows and stuck them into their father's breast. Then, the youngest refused to shoot, saying, "I will rather lose all than wound that body that I so loved living. Had you ever had but half that love for him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled than to suffer his lifeless corpse to be used. Nay, you do not only suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame." And speaking this, he wept.

In the matter, the king was very glad hereof and caused the combatants to be brought before him. To them, he said, "Gentlemen, to save the blood of you all, I have found a way, and yet the controversy shall be ended that is now amongst you. Are you contented to stand to his judgment that I shall appoint?" They all answered that they were. Then they were asked to return three days later. 

During this time, Friar Bacon had exhumed the body of their deceased father and brought it to the court. He then bound the body to a stake, leaving it naked from the middle upwards. He likewise prepared three bows and arrows for the three brothers. All of these he kept in secret. 

On the third day, the three brothers returned. Friar Bacon then gave them the three bows and arrows in the presence of the king, saying, "Be not offended at what I have done. There is no other way to judge your cause but this. See here is the body of your dead father. Shoot at him for he that comes nearest to his heart shall have all the lands and goods." 

The two eldest brothers shot their arrows and stuck them into their father's breast. Then, the youngest refused to shoot, saying, "I will rather lose all than wound that body that I so loved living. Had you ever had but half that love for him that I have, you would rather have had your own bodies mangled than to suffer his lifeless corpse to be used. Nay, you do not only suffer it, but you are the actors of this act of shame." And speaking this, he wept.

Then it fortuned upon a day the Priour and his brethren were assembled together in a generall counsaile, and as they stood talking together, the Priour remembered Rush, and anon he said unto his brethren Friends we have here Rush which is our maister Cooke in our kitchin, and he is an olde servant, and much diligent and true service he hath done to us, and he hath continued among us longer then any servant that ever wee had wherefore me thinke it reason, that hee were promoted into some other office, and made a brother among us. Then all the whole Covent with one voice said they were content it should so be. So the Priour sent for Rush, and when he was come before him and all his brethren, the Priour said, Rush it is so, thou hast beene here a long season, and we have found thee hitherto a true and diligent servant, wherefore wee will that thou be promoted, and take upon thee an habite as we have, and to become a brother among us. Rush answered and said my Maisters I thanke you all, and then the Priour gave Rush an habite, and put it on his backe, and so Rush became a brother in the place, neverthelesse he kept his office still. How Frier Rush made Truncheons for the Friers to fight withall. WHEN Rush had on the habite of a Frier, and was a brother in the place, he had more vacation dayes

When Rush had put on the habit of a friar and had become a brother in the place, he had more vacation days than when he was a student.
prediction.region: than before, and he began to devise mischiefs. One day, he saw the brethren of the Covent quarrelling among themselves, and he thought how he could make things worse. Rush then took some truncheons and sharpened them like swords, and gave them to the Friers, telling them to use them against each other. The Friers accepted the truncheons and began to fight with great violence. One of them was severely injured, and the rest were badly hurt, creating chaos in the Covent. Rush then pretended to be shocked by what had happened and claimed to have no idea how the truncheons had gotten into the hands of the Friers. Rush was scolded by the Priour, and he acted as though he was sorry. However, he continued to do bad things, and his behavior became even worse than before.

Elle s'excusait d'avoir si peu  offrir, et priait qu'on lui tint compte de l'intention saps s'arrter  la valeur des choses. Chaque legs tait d'ailleurs appropri  la personne avec un soin dlicat qui y ajoutait un nouveau prix. Marguerite eut une dernire attention elle laissa son se-crtaire ouvert et plaa sur la tablette la pice qui rendait Ludovic matre de tout rgler chez elle et d'agir  son gr. Prs du testament tait l'anneau, ce triste et mystrieux em-blme. Ds le premier abord les yeux devaient se porter sur ces objets, et le jeune homme y reconnatrait quelles avaient t, au moment de quitter ce monde, la pense de la mou-rante et sa proccupation. Quand elle en eut fini avec la terre, Marguerite songea au ciel elle s'agenouilla devant le portrait de sa grand'mre et pria avec ferveur. Que fut cette prire? Sans doute un acte de contritipp et en mme temps un cri de dsespoir. Elle prit Dieu  tmoin, et, lui montrant l'tat de son me, invo-qua sa misricorde ayec un accent plor. Puis s'adressant  cette aeule qui avait si saintement vcu et si saintement fini,  sa mre moissonne avant le temps et qui, son mari mort, avait, elle aussi, manqu de courage, elle les conjura sans doute d'intercder pour elle et d'obtenir qu'elle ft admise  leurs cts, daps le sjour des mes pures ou purifies par le repentir. Elle leur demanda d'unir leurs prires  la sienne afin d'en augmenter l'effet et d'ob-tenir ce pardon qui descend d'en haut sur les coeurs humi-lis et sincres. Quand elle eut mis sa conscience en paix, autant que le permettait l'acte violent auquel elle tait rsolue, elle monta sur son lit, ajusta ses vtements de manire  ce que rien n'y pt amener du dsordre, s'tendit sur les coussins, et, s'emparant d'une petite fiole qui tait  sa porte, elle l'ap-procha de ses lvres. 1 Quelques minutes aprs , elle tait plonge dans un en-gourdissement profond.

At last there grew such foule words betweenc them, and their bloods were so heated, that they presently stabbed one the other with their daggers, and so fell downe dead. Fryer Bacon seeing them fall, ranne to them, but it was too late, for they were breathlesse ere he came. This made him to grieve exceedingly be iudging that they had received the cause of their deaths by this glasse, tooke the glasse in his hand, aud uttered words to this effect Wretched Bacon, wretched in thy knowledge, in thy understanding wretched for thy art hath beene the ruine of these two gentlemen. Had I been busied in those holy things, the which mine order tyes me to, I had not had that time that made this wicked glasse wicked I weU may cad it, that is the causer of so vde an act would it were sensible, then should it feele my wrath but being as it is, He ruin it for ruining of them and with that he broke his rare and wonderftdl glasse, whose Hke the whole world had not. In this grief of his, came there newes to him of the deaths of Vandermast and Fryer Bungey This did increase his griefe, and made him sorrowfull, that in three days he would not eate any thing but kept his chamber.

CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE, page 269.

ocr.sentence: J'tais une fille dshonore !
ocr.region: CE QU'ON PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE. 269 o cette scne se passait. Par le concours des circonstances, j'tais compromise  un point qu'aucune rparation n'tait possible, si ce n'est celle que pouvait m'offrir Melcbior. Son but tait atteint il m'avait mise  la discrtion de son hon-neur. Triste garantie ! et je le vis bien plus tard. Je succombai une barrire s'leva entre vous et moi je ne pouvais plus tre  vous, Ludovic. Les heures s'cou-laient il fallut prendre un parti. Encore quelques instants, et vous alliez venir chercher votre fiance impossible de vous attendre en vous voyant je serais tombe morte  vos pieds. Nous primes donc, Melchior et moi, nos dernires dis-positions. Au petit jour, et quand la porte fut ouverte, il quitta la maison. Un rendez-vous avait t fix, et je devais aller le rejoindre. Il passa sans tre aperu peut-tre le concierge tait-il son complice. Quant  moi, je restai pendant une heure encore abme dans mes regrets et mes remords. -Toutes vos bonts me revinrent alors  la mmoire, et je me trouvai bien ingrate, bien cruelle et en mme temps bien dchue. -Qu'ai liez-vous penser de moi? Hlas 1 quoi que vous pussiez en penser, la ralit dpasserait vos suppositions. J'tais une fille dshonore ! XXX - Pourtant, Ludovic, je vous crivis quelques mots, non pas tels que j'aurais voulu les crire, mais assez prcis pour que dsormais vous me regardassiez comme perdue pour vous. Puis j'enlevai de mon doigt l'anneau qui me venait de ma grand'mre et qui avait si mal prserv mon honneur. Je n'tais plus digne de le porter, quoi qu'il arrivt et de quel-que faon que tournassent les choses. Je rejoignis Melchior et le trouvai ivre de son bonheur. Moi-mme,  ce premier moment, j'prouvai ce vertige des sens qui n'est que la fausse monnaie de l'amour. Melchior

Legrand, tu prends le secteur H, dangereux pour les marmites, surtout au Bois Equerre tu suivras le boyau central jusqu'au boyau Boscary, o tu trouveras le poste de son com-mandant. Attention vous autres, baissez la tte, les balles tra-versent la route! Je garde deux hommes avec moi au poste du colonel,  la borne 16. La nuit tait venne, pas de lune, une obscurit complte rgnait sur les tranches, et sauf les coups de fusils espacs, partant des premires lignes, la soire tait calme. Les fuses dans le ciel irradiaient par moments l'horizon de leur courbe gracieuse, inondant les parapets d'une lueur blafarde. L'quipe se spara en deux. Puis,  la file, les nouveaux venus longrent la route le plus prs possible du remblai pour viter les balles perdues qui froufroutaient avec un bruit de soie, allant frapper les troncs d'arbres de l'autre ct du ruis-seau. -Pour une belle nuit, c'est une belle nuit, remarqua R-gnier, un combat de ngres sous un tunnel et  chaque fuse il gouaillait Ah! la belle bleue! -Allez, activez le mouvement, lana Legrand impatient, en laissant derrire lui Duruy qui entrait dans son boyau, nous avons encore un bout de chemin! Sans se dtourner il poursuivit sa marche  ttons, cher-chant  chaque trou la pancarte indicatrice.

ocr.sentence: CE PEUT VOIR DANS UNE RUE.
ocr.region: CE qu'on PEUT VOIR DANS UNE rue. 257, j'obis, tant il y avait en moi de confusion et de trouble. Il faut si. peu de chose pour arrter une confidence sur les lvres, surtout lorsqu'il s'agit de s'accuser d'un tort et de se mettre  la merci d'autrui ! On s'empare alors du premier prtexte, le plus futile, le plus spcieux on recule, on ajourne, et, dans ces ajournements mmes, -on puise des mo-tifs pour s'abstenir. C'est ce qui m'arriva, Ludovic. Avant- de vous revoir, j'tais rsolue  tout vous dire, et quand je vous revis la confiance me manqua. LES TLPHONISTES DANS LA BATAILLE

- Dans deux heures. O est notre poste ?
- J'en sais rien.
- Merci !

Et sans se dcourager, il continua en s'adressant  des soldats qui tiraillaient quelques cartouches.

- C'est les tlphonistes.
- Ah, les planqus ! chuchotrent les hommes.
- Oui, planqus en premire ligne comme vous autres, rpondit Rgnier avec colre, et il continua  poser des questions. - Le poste tlphonique ?
- Taisez-vous, souffla un sergent, nous sommes  vingt mtres des Boches !

Soudain, une tte surgit d'un trou et un bras lui fit signe d'approcher.

- C'est nous, fit Rgnier, o est le poste ?
- Il n'y en a pas, rpondit une voix, on est entasss dans un abri !

Couch presque  plat ventre, Rgnier se glissa dans l'excavation.

- C'est maigre, miladiou ! murmura-t-il. Enfin.

Accroupi, repli sur lui-mme, il parvint tant bien que mal  tablir sa communication.

- Allo ! Caporal Legrand, c'est vous ? C'est Rgnier qui est  l'appareil. Bon. a marche. Vous dites ? Ah ! oui, je crois que le climat n'est pas sain, vu l'humidit. J'ai peur de prendre racine. Je sens dj des fourmis dans les jambes. Allez, bonne nuit, Caporal.

- Dites donc, vous n'tes pas l pour faire la causette, fit brusquement un adjudant, fermez a une fois pour toutes.

Le mieux pour lui tait de se taire, car il sentait une atmosphre hostile. Les deux soldats qui partaient mirent leurs sacs sur le dos, se quittrent en se serrant la main et s'loignrent rapidement.

- Ce n'est pas confortable l-dedans, soupira le Mridional assis en tailleur. J'ai des crampes dans les genoux, mais ce qui me console, c'est que je ne paie pas mon loyer !

La nuit s'annonait assez calme, fatigus par les attaques des jours prcdents, les Allemands paraissaient plutt inquiets qu'agressifs. Buchard, insensible et bris de fatigue, s'tait endormi. Seul Rgnier veillait et comme il n'avait personne  qui parler, il se mit  manger un morceau de singe et  finir le reste de vin.

Soudain une tte surgit d'un trou et un bras lui lit signe d'approcher. - C'est nous, fit Rgnier, o est le poste? - Y en a pas, rpondit une voix, on est tasss dans un gourbi! Couch presque  plat ventre, Rgnier se raunJa dans l'exca-vation. - C'est maigre, miladious! murmura-t-il, enQn.! Accroupi, ramass sur lui-mme, 11 tablit tant bien que mal sa communication. - Allo! caporal Legrand, c'est vous?. C'est Rgnier qui est  l'appareil. Bon. a marche. Vous dites?. Ah! oui, je crois que le climat n'est pas sain, vu l'humidit. J'ai peur de prendre racine. Je me sens dj des fourmis dans les jambes. Al-lons, bonne nuit, caporal. - Dites donc, vous n'tes pas l pour faire la causette, fit brusquement un adjudant, fermez a une fois pour toutes. Le mieux pour lui tait de ne pas rpliquer, car il se sentait dans une atmosphre hostile. - Taisez-vous, souffla un sergent, nous sommes  vingt mtres des Boches !

Soudain, une tte surgit d'un trou et un bras lui fit signe d'approcher.

- C'est nous, fit Rgnier, o est le poste ?
- Il n'y en a pas, rpondit une voix, on est entasss dans un abri !

- C'est maigre, miladiou ! murmura-t-il. Enfin.

Accroupi, repli sur lui-mme, il parvint tant bien que mal  tablir sa communication.

- Allo ! Caporal Legrand, c'est vous ? C'est Rgnier qui est  l'appareil. Bon. a marche. Vous dites ? Ah ! oui, je crois que le climat n'est pas sain, vu l'humidit. J'ai peur de prendre racine. Je sens dj des fourmis dans les jambes. Allez, bonne nuit, Caporal.

Le mieux pour lui tait de se taire, car il sentait une atmosphre hostile. Les deux soldats qui partaient mirent leurs sacs sur le dos, se quittrent en se serrant la main et s'loignrent rapidement.

- Ce n'est pas confortable l-dedans, soupira le Mridional assis en tailleur. J'ai des crampes dans les genoux, mais ce qui me console, c'est que je ne paie pas mon loyer !

ocr.region: 277 OF FRIER RUSH. then he said to Rush, thou lew d fellow, what bast thou done to this waggon that I am thus arayed therein ? Rush answered and said sir, I have done nothing but as you commanded me. That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to makeready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another babite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour caUed for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and bis fellowes sate downe to the rever sions that their maisters bad left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they caUed for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

That is not, said the Priour, for I commaunded thee to take greace and grease but the wheeles and the axeltrees, and thou hast taken tarre and annointed it all over, both within and without. Why hast thou done so ? Sir said Rush, I understoode you bad me doe so. And when the Priour sawe there was no other remedie, he commanded his servants to make ready another waggon, and in the meane season, the Priour went into his chamber, and put on another habite, and came againe and mounted into the waggon and went their way, and so long they rode, that they came to their iourneyes end. And when they were alighted at their lodging, the Priour called for his supper, and anon every thing was made ready, and the good man of the house and the Priour sate downe to supper together, and made good cheere and then the Priour called for wine of the best, and anon he had his commandement. And when the good man of the house and the Priour had supped, Rush and his fellowes sate downe to the rever-sions that their maisters had left, but they had no wine wherefore Rush was very sad, and ever he mused by what policie he might get some wine. And anon he called the wife of the house and said Mistresse, I pray you fill a pottle of wine for me and my fellowes, and so shee did and when that was gone, they called for another and then they called for the third, and so ended their

The Friers were amazed at the voice of Rush, and knew not from whence it came, nor how he had come by the candell. prediction.sentence: And when Friar Rush saw that they were fighting together, he immediately blew out all the candles and lamps that were burning in the church, leaving no light for them to see each other. He then took his truncheon in his hand and went into the choir among the thickest of the friars who were fighting without light and there he laid about so lustily that many of them fell to the ground, and were left there for dead. When he had finished, he stole his way from them. As he went, he found a great old desk standing in the portal of the choir. He took the desk between both his hands and threw it over the portal into the choir, among all the friars, hurting many of them sorely. Some had an arm or a leg broken, and others had their noses cleanly pared from their faces, with blood running in their mouths. There were no dainty broken heads, every man had one. If someone had been there, they would have had a good time watching the friars crawl around the choir crying out "alas and well away" instead of "Domine labia.

The Friers were amazed at the voice of Rush, and knew not from whence it came, nor how he had come by the candell. And they answered him, that they knew not how the discord began, nor whence came that man which had disturbed their feasting, and so Rush departed from them, and went to the gate of the covent. And there he taried a long while, and none came to him, nor spake to him. And so he departed thence with great mirth, and went unto his master, and told him all that he had done among the Friers. And his master laughed heartily thereat, and gave to him a new suit of raiment, and commanded him to go forth and do more such pranks among the religious men.

prediction.sentence: Another time, it befell that the Prior had to journey into the country for a small matter that needed attending to. He called for his servant Rush and said, "Rush, go into the courtyard and take a dish of grease, and grease the wheels and axles of the wagon. Make all things ready for tomorrow morning, for I must leave early." Rush left his master and went to do his duty. However, instead of grease, he took a great vessel full of tar and smeared it all over the wagon, inside and out. He made sure to apply it thickly where the Prior would sit. When Rush finished, he returned to the Prior's chamber. The Prior asked Rush if he had done as commanded, and Rush replied, "Yes sir, you may ride whenever you please." They both went to sleep.

Then, all of a sudden, the Prior came into the choir and took his seat. As he looked around, he noticed that the Sub-Prior was also present. His heart started to grudge with old anger that had fallen between the two of them. In his mind, he thought that there could be no better time to seek revenge. Suddenly, he rose from his seat and went towards the Sub-Prior. With his fist, he gave him a good blow, which angered the Sub-Prior. In return, he too hit the Prior. They started fighting, and the other friars, who witnessed the fight, also got up from their seats and drew their batons. Together, they all began to beat each other up.

They being not contented with this tryall of their skill, went further in their coniurations, and raised up two spirits, each of them one. Bungye charged his spirit for to assist him with the greatest power hee had, that by it he might be able to overcome Vandermast. The Devdl told him he would, if that he from his left arme would give him but three drops of blood but if that he did deny him that, then should Vandermast have power over him to doe what he would the Hke told Vandermasts Devill to him to this demand of the spirits, they both agreed, thinking for to overcome each other but the Devill overthrew them both. They having given the Devill this bloud, as is before spoken of, they both fell againe to their coniurations first, Bungye did rayse Achilles with bis Greekes, who marched about Vandermast and threatned him. Then Vandermast raised Hector with his Troians, who defended him from AchiUes and the Greekes. Then began there a great batteU between the Greekes and Troians, which continued a good space at last Hector was slaine, and the Troians fled. Then did follow a great tempest, with thundring and lightning, so that the two coniurers wished that they had been away. But wishes were in vaine for now the time was come, that the Devill would be paid for the knowledge that he had

Correct the spelling and grammar of the following text: 264 A PLEASANT HISTORIE good and well disposed people, they spent in unthrifti nesse and rybauldry. And when the great prince of devils which are the patrones of aU vices understood of the great misrule and rile living of these religious men consulted to keepe them still in that state, and worse if it might be. And these be the names of the devils.
